files.name: hydro_serving_grpc/tf/tensor_shape.proto
files.description: Protocol buffer representing the shape of tensors.

fields.name: dim
fields.description:
Dimensions of the tensor, such as {"input", 30}, {"output", 40}
for a 30 x 40 2D tensor.  If an entry has size -1, this
corresponds to a dimension of unknown size. The names are
optional.

The order of entries in "dim" matters: It indicates the layout of the
values in the tensor in-memory representation.

The first entry in "dim" is the outermost dimension used to layout the
values, the last entry is the innermost dimension.  This matches the
in-memory layout of RowMajor Eigen tensors.

If "dim.size()" > 0, "unknown_rank" must be false.
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: unknown_rank
fields.description:
If true, the number of dimensions in the shape is unknown.

If true, "dim.size()" must be 0.

fields.name: size
fields.description:
Size of the tensor in that dimension.
This value must be >= -1, but values of -1 are reserved for "unknown"
shapes (values of -1 mean "unknown" dimension).  Certain wrappers
that work with TensorShapeProto may fail at runtime when deserializing
a TensorShapeProto containing a dim value of -1.

fields.name: name
fields.description: Optional name of the tensor dimension.

values.name: DT_INVALID
values.description:
Not a legal value for DataType.  Used to indicate a DataType field
has not been set.

values.name: DT_FLOAT
values.description:
Data types that all computation devices are expected to be
capable to support.

values.name: DT_BFLOAT16
values.description: Float32 truncated to 16 bits.  Only for cast ops.

values.name: DT_MAP
values.description: Hydroserving map structure inside the tensor

messages.name: PredictRequest
messages.description:
PredictRequest specifies which TensorFlow model to run, as well as
how inputs are mapped to tensors and how outputs are filtered before
returning to user.

fields.name: model_spec
fields.description: Model Specification.

fields.name: inputs
fields.description:
Input tensors.
Names of input tensor are alias names. The mapping from aliases to real
input tensor names is stored in the SavedModel export as a prediction
SignatureDef under the 'inputs' field.
fields.label: repeated

messages.name: PredictResponse
messages.description: Response for PredictRequest on successful run.

fields.name: outputs
fields.description: Output tensors.
fields.label: repeated

methods.name: Status
methods.description: Ask for a status. Could contain explanation.

messages.name: ModelSpec
messages.description: Metadata for an inference request such as the model name and version.

fields.name: name
fields.description: Required servable name.

fields.name: version
fields.description:
Optional version. If unspecified, will use the latest (numerical) version.
Typically not needed unless coordinating across multiple models that were
co-trained and/or have inter-dependencies on the versions used at inference
time.

fields.name: signature_name
fields.description:
A named signature to evaluate. If unspecified, the default signature will
be used.

fields.name: tensor_shape
fields.description: Shape of the tensor.

fields.name: version_number
fields.description:
Version number.

In version 0, if the "repeated xxx" representations contain only one
element, that element is repeated to fill the shape.  This makes it easy
to represent a constant Tensor with a single value.

fields.name: tensor_content
fields.description:
Serialized raw tensor content from either Tensor::AsProtoTensorContent or
memcpy in tensorflow::grpc::EncodeTensorToByteBuffer. This representation
can be used for all tensor types. The purpose of this representation is to
reduce serialization overhead during RPC call by avoiding serialization of
many repeated small items.

fields.name: half_val
fields.description:
DT_HALF. Note that since protobuf has no int16 type, we'll have some
pointless zero padding for each value here.
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: float_val
fields.description: DT_FLOAT.
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: double_val
fields.description: DT_DOUBLE.
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: int_val
fields.description: DT_INT32, DT_INT16, DT_INT8, DT_UINT8.
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: string_val
fields.description: DT_STRING
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: scomplex_val
fields.description:
DT_COMPLEX64. scomplex_val(2*i) and scomplex_val(2*i+1) are real
and imaginary parts of i-th single precision complex.
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: int64_val
fields.description: DT_INT64
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: bool_val
fields.description: DT_BOOL
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: dcomplex_val
fields.description:
DT_COMPLEX128. dcomplex_val(2*i) and dcomplex_val(2*i+1) are real
and imaginary parts of i-th double precision complex.
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: variant_val
fields.description: DT_VARIANT
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: uint32_val
fields.description: DT_UINT32
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: uint64_val
fields.description: DT_UINT64
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: map_val
fields.description: Hydroserving
fields.label: repeated

messages.name: VariantTensorDataProto
messages.description: Protocol buffer representing the serialization format of DT_VARIANT tensors.

fields.name: type_name
fields.description: Name of the type of objects being serialized.

fields.name: metadata

fields.name: tensors
fields.description: Tensors contained within objects being serialized.
fields.label: repeated

scalarValueTypes.notes: Uses variable-length encoding. Inefficient for encoding negative numbers  if your field is likely to have negative values, use sint32 instead.
Uses variable-length encoding. Inefficient for encoding negative numbers  if your field is likely to have negative values, use sint64 instead.
Uses variable-length encoding. Signed int value. These more efficiently encode negative numbers than regular int32s.
Uses variable-length encoding. Signed int value. These more efficiently encode negative numbers than regular int64s.
Always four bytes. More efficient than uint32 if values are often greater than 2^28.
Always eight bytes. More efficient than uint64 if values are often greater than 2^56.
A string must always contain UTF-8 encoded or 7-bit ASCII text.
May contain any arbitrary sequence of bytes.
